In Chrome (Version 26.0.1410.64 m), there is a bug that blocks you from editing a file.

Steps to reproduce :

* Click on a file;
* Click on the Edit button;
* Click on the Cancel button;
* Click again on the Edit button.

The wait spinner will spin forever.

I access my site from different machines.  It would be extremely useful to be able to track a "current" filter (built up interactively by clicking and sorting) on each machine, for example:

{code}
#!html

issues?status=new&status=open&priority=critical&responsible=gamesbook&sort=-created_on
{code}

If this could be allocated, via a simple click to, a "favourite" spot on the same row as the other filtters(see attachments), that would be very convenient.

In my readme code I have:

{code}
#!markdown

###`/getcollections`

Returns all available collections which each represent a field through which ch\
anges can be tracked. Optionally returns a count of the number of records avail\
able in each collection.

**param** *count*

: optional. boolean.

**returns**

: json string of two possible formats:

    {
        names: [
            <string>,
            ...
        ]
    }

OR

    [
        {
            name:   <string>,
            count:  <int>
        },
        ...
    ]
{code}

This renders as\\
!http://nytlabs.com/bitbucket_issue/bitbucketrender.png!

When it should render as\\
!http://nytlabs.com/bitbucket_issue/workingrender.png!

Hash signs followed by a digit render with an extra backslash in syntax highlighted Markdown code fragments. This happens in the issue tracker, possibly also other situations where Markdown or the syntax highlighter is involved.

Example:

{code}
BCLOUD-3
{code}

{code}
BCLOUD-3
{code}

Expected:

{{#3}}

Diffs in mails often include next lines into diff line (removing newlines ?).

